Interesting question. My answer: every possible relationship and mutual bond conceivable by writers should be examined and explored /in/ writing. That's what writing is for, Anon – it's your medium, your vehicle by which to convey your ideas and concepts with mine, others, and - in accord with your goals - your target demographics.
Relations founded on mutual love are not clear-cut — they are only even partly physical. People who endure the same or similar hardships (trauma, strife, combat, etc.), who can relate to one another emotionally, are going to fall in love for different reasons than are common in modern civil courtship. Partners who seem compatible may vie with one another and dissolve as their dynamic is tested, situations change, and needs - extant & as-yet-undiscovered - are unmet. Good people can become disappointed in one another, or they can change entirely when crises emerge.
Likewise, incompatible people, bitter rivals, etc., can find love in one another. Bullies can find emotional security and love in their targets, rival assassins can fall in love with one another, so on and so forth. We all live vicariously through fiction – if you can imagine it, then it deserves consideration, whether you commit it to writ or not. Personally, I do not at all believe in anything being absolutely beyond the realm of possibility, ESPECIALLY in something so dynamic, complex, & adaptable as romance. More importantly, n o t h i n g is impossible in creative fiction writing. Take the most compatible people in the universe and tear them apart; show us how two people, with nothing but the hottest enmity for one another, might find mutual peace and joy in one another's arms.

That's where I sit. My lust for fresh experience and ideas is only matched by my unshakable love for pleasing (or viscerally disemboweling) others with my own. Not every journey ends in the placid pastures of pastoral paintings & pleasant pastimes. Give us non-sequitur high notes.
